could you please evaluate the performance comparing to the following implementation?

```
#include <atomic>
class SpinLock {
public:
    void lock()  {
        while(lck.test_and_set(std::memory_order_acquire))
        {}
    }

    void unlock()   {
        lck.clear(std::memory_order_release);
    }

private:
    std::atomic_flag lck = ATOMIC_FLAG_INIT;
};
```

No, you cannot remove the union def, I think you can move the type T ahead of the next, and see if that works for you. To change it to

```
 struct LinkedList {
      T t;
      LinkedList* next{nullptr};
  };
```

I have found where the invalid pointer locates.
In `ndarray.h`, line `470`:

```
  inline NDArrayFunctionReg &set_function(void fsetvalue(const real_t &rhs,
                                                         NDArray *out)) {
    body = [fsetvalue] (NDArray **used_vars, real_t *s, NDArray **mutate_vars) {
      fsetvalue(s[0], mutate_vars[0]);
    };
```

When the program goes to `fsetvalue`, it seems that the `fsetvalue` is no longer the one registered to function list. When I replace the formal paramter with std::function, the problem solved. 

```
  inline NDArrayFunctionReg &set_function(std::function<void (const real_t &rhs,
    NDArray *out)> fsetvalue) {
    body = [fsetvalue] (NDArray **used_vars, real_t *s, NDArray **mutate_vars) {
      fsetvalue(s[0], mutate_vars[0]);
    };
```

I started to learn C++11 just a few days ago, so I don't know why it works.
